posts.title: Iranian official tells CNN Tehran wants the US to "pay" for its attacks "directly"
posts.author: From CNN’s Fred Pleitgen
posts.imageCaption: Iranians lift flags and chant during a rally protesting the US attack on Iran in Enghelab Square in Tehran, Iran, on Sunday. Atta Kenare/AFP/Getty Images
posts.content:
# Iran Demands US to Pay for War Effort

The Iranian government wants the **United States** to “directly pay for the war, rather than standing behind Israel and pursue its project without having to pay the cost,” a senior Iranian official told **CNN** on Monday.

The decision by **US President Donald Trump** to order strikes against three Iranian nuclear sites on Sunday sparked a wave of **anti-US sentiment** in Iran, with many calling for retaliation.

## Growing Protests and Rising Tensions

A large **anti-US** and **anti-Israel** protest took place in **Tehran** on Sunday evening, with many in the crowd demanding revenge. **Israel launched a surprise attack on Iran 11 days ago**, and the two countries have been striking each other daily since, leaving hundreds of people dead.

> “Morale is high and the immense demand by the Iranian people to strike Israel is unprecedented,” the official told CNN, adding that calls by the Iranian public to strike Israel are “an element in intensifying Iran’s battle plans.”

## Iran’s Strategy Moving Forward

The official further stated that Iran believed calls for a temporary pause in the war were a **“deception in order to assess Iran’s preparedness for continuing the war.”**

They also added that Iran estimated the conflict **could last up to two years**, and emphasized that **Iran was prepared for that**.

posts.title: Fresh Israeli strikes hit Tehran as Iran's top diplomat meets with Putin in Moscow. Here's what we know
posts.author: From CNN staff
posts.imageCaption: Source: Maxar Technologies, CNN analysis of satellite imagery  Graphic: Thomas Bordeaux and Rosa de Acosta, CNN
posts.content:
# Escalating Tensions: Israel Launches New Strikes in Tehran Amidst Diplomatic Efforts and Regional Concerns

---

**Tehran, Iran** – **Israel launched a fresh wave of strikes in Tehran today** as Iran’s Foreign Minister Abbas Araghchi met with Russian President Vladimir Putin in Moscow. Araghchi’s meeting comes as **Iran considers its response to recent US strikes on its nuclear facilities.** Yesterday, the Iranian foreign minister urged UN Secretary-General António Guterres to condemn the US government in the “strongest possible terms” for these strikes.

Meanwhile, a source indicated that Israel could achieve most of its operational goals in Iran “within days.”

---

## Key Developments

* **Iran’s Top Diplomat in Moscow:** During their meeting, **Putin condemned US attacks on Iran** and reassured the Iranian delegation of Russia's support. He informed Araghchi that he had spoken with US President Donald Trump, Israel’s Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, President of the United Arab Emirates Mohammed Al Nahyan, and Iranian President Masoud Pezeshkian, without specifying the dates of these conversations. Araghchi expressed gratitude for Putin's support, stating that Russia was “on the right side of history.”

* **Israeli Strikes Target Nuclear Facility Access and Prison:** The Israel Defense Forces (IDF) today announced **strikes on access routes to the Fordow nuclear facility in central Iran**. In a brief statement, the IDF explained the strikes were carried out “in order to obstruct” access to the enrichment facility, which had been attacked by the US with bunker-buster bombs 36 hours prior. The Israeli military also attacked the entrance of Iran’s **notorious Evin prison**, according to Israel’s defense minister and Iranian state news, as part of its latest salvo on the capital, Tehran.

* **Iran Retaliates with Missile Strikes on Israel:** Earlier today, Israel identified **additional missiles launched from Iran toward its northern region**, the IDF reported, adding that it was working to intercept them. The military advised the public to seek and remain in shelters. A wave of Iranian missiles **disrupted the electricity supply to “several communities” in southern Israel**, as confirmed by Israel’s electricity company.

---

## Broader Implications

* **Economic Concerns Intensify:** The weekend strikes have amplified what Kristalina Georgieva, head of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), described as an already **“highly uncertain environment.”** The IMF is closely monitoring for further upward pressure on oil and natural gas prices and any potential disruption to global energy supplies stemming from the conflict in the oil-rich Middle East, she told Bloomberg TV.

* **Calls for De-escalation:** **China has called for greater international effort to de-escalate the Israel-Iran conflict** to prevent further impact on the global economy. This comes amidst growing calls within Iran for closing the Strait of Hormuz in retaliation for US strikes on its nuclear sites.

* **White House Responds:** White House press secretary Karoline Leavitt **reiterated Trump’s claim** that Iran’s nuclear sites were “completely and totally obliterated.” Addressing Trump’s comments regarding regime change in Iran, Leavitt stated that the US military posture remains unchanged. “The president was just simply raising a question that I think many people around the world are asking, if the Iranian regime refuses to give up their nuclear program or engage in talks,” she told reporters.

posts.title: LA County Sheriff apologizes for social media post that offered condolences for “victims” in Iran
posts.author: From CNN's Chelsea Bailey
posts.imageCaption: A file photo of Los Angeles County Sheriff Robert G. Luna. (CNN)
posts.content:
# LA Sheriff's Department Apologizes for Controversial Iran Bombings Post

---

The Los Angeles County Sheriff’s Department has issued an apology for a social media post that caused controversy on Sunday. The original post, shared across the department’s official social media accounts, offered condolences to the "victims and families impacted by the recent bombings in Iran."

The post stated that while the "tragic event occurred overseas," the department would be "closely monitoring the situation" and that "at the moment, there are no known threats to Los Angeles County." However, it added that "out of an abundance of caution, we are increasing patrol checks at places of worship and other sensitive locations throughout the county."

This message quickly drew **backlash online**. Critics accused the sheriff's office of stoking fear, while others questioned the post's tone and its sympathy for Iran. One commenter stated, "The original post was very thoughtless and a slap in the face to the American people, our service men and women, as well as to Israel. Unbelievable!"

The department later issued a lengthy statement, apologizing for the "**offensive and inappropriate social media post**." They clarified that "we do not comment on foreign policy or military matters" and that the post "does not reflect the views of Sheriff Robert R. Luna or the Department."

The Greater Los Angeles area is home to the largest diaspora of Iranian immigrants in the United States, with over a third of Iranian immigrants in the US residing in the Los Angeles area, according to the Migration Policy Institute.

The department concluded its apology by stating, "We fully recognize that the words and messages we share carry weight. We have updated our social media post and have launched an internal review to determine how it was created and published."

posts.title: Analysis: Why regime change in Iran is no simple matter
posts.author: From CNN’s Nadeen Ebrahim
posts.imageCaption: Iran's Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei speaks during a meeting in Tehran, Iran, on January 1. Office of the Iranian Supreme Leader/WANA/Reuters
posts.content:
# Experts Warn Against Unforeseen Consequences of Iran "Regime Change"

---

US President Donald Trump has hinted at “regime change” in Iran, but experts caution that the prospect may not be as simple as he thinks, and its outcomes seem unlikely to align with Washington's envisioned goals.

Experts warn that **regime change in Iran won’t guarantee a government that is friendly to the United States or Israel**. Instead, it could potentially pave the way for more hawkish figures who might race to develop a nuclear bomb as the ultimate deterrent, especially following the destruction caused by American and Israeli strikes.

While **Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei can be replaced if he is killed**, experts note that US officials also need to factor in the risk of **regime failure**. This could splinter the country and send shockwaves across the entire Middle East.

Another possible outcome is that **elements within the Iranian military could assume power**. These factions are “not going to be the type of regime that the US may have had in mind,” Trita Parsi, executive vice president of the Quincy Institute in Washington, DC, told CNN.

> Home to long-simmering separatist movements that have vied for power and independence, Iran could face internal fragmentation and chaos if its government falls entirely, experts warn.

“Regime collapse is just to collapse the state, and let the chaos that ensues fester,” Parsi told CNN.

The supreme leader is elected for life by the 88-member Assembly of Experts and doesn’t officially name a successor. However, *The New York Times reported on Saturday* that Khamenei has named three senior clerics as candidates to succeed him should he be killed, citing three Iranian officials familiar with the matter.

Any replacement process may occur as **separatist groups who have long resented the Islamic Republic seek to take advantage of what they may see as an opportunity.**

posts.title: Thousands rally in Kenya to mark anniversary of antitax demonstrations
posts.author: Source: News Agencies
posts.imageCaption: A protester reacts in front of a burning barricade in downtown Nairobi, Kenya, June 25, 2025 [Luis Tato/AFP]
posts.content:
Thousands of people have taken to the streets in Kenya to mark a year since people stormed parliament at the peak of antigovernment demonstrations, despite fears that they would be met by state-backed gangs and police violence.

At least 60 people were killed last year by security forces in weeks of protests over tax rises and the dire economic situation for young Kenyans, rights groups say. On Wednesday, activists and families of victims called for peaceful demonstrations to mark the anniversary of the deadliest day of unrest.

Police blocked main roads leading into the capital’s central business district, while government buildings were barricaded with razor wire.

Thousands of protesters, mostly young men, waved Kenyan flags and placards with pictures of demonstrators killed last year and chanted “Ruto must go”, referring to President William Ruto, whose proposed tax hikes triggered last year’s youth-led protests.

“I’ve come here as a Kenyan youth to protest, it is our right for the sake of our fellow Kenyans who were killed last year. The police are here … they are supposed to protect us, but they kill us,”
— Eve, a 24-year-old woman, told the AFP news agency.

“It is extremely important that the young people mark June 25th because they lost people who look like them, who speak like them… who are fighting for good governance,”
— Angel Mbuthia, chair of the youth league for the opposition Jubilee Party.

Police brutality

The anniversary comes amid soaring anger over police brutality, particularly after 31-year-old blogger and teacher, Albert Ojwang, was killed in custody earlier this month following his arrest for criticising a senior officer.

Six people, including three police officers, were charged with murder on Tuesday over Ojwang’s killing. They have all pleaded not guilty.

Police have said protests are permitted as long as they are “peaceful and unarmed”.

But a group of peaceful protesters were attacked last week by a large gang of motorbike-riding “goons”, as they are known in Kenya, armed with whips and clubs and working in tandem with the police.

On Tuesday, the embassies of the United States, the United Kingdom, Canada, and other Western nations released a joint statement on X urging all involved to “facilitate peaceful demonstrations and to refrain from violence”.

“The use of plain clothed officers in unmarked vehicles erodes public trust,” the statement said.

Rights campaigners condemned the presence of unidentified police officers at protests last year.

Kenya’s Ministry of Foreign Affairs said in a statement late on Tuesday that any policing violations would be addressed through government institutions, including the parliament and the judiciary.

“The ministry reminds all that diplomatic partnerships flourish best in mutual respect, open channels and a recognition of each other’s unique governance contexts,” it said.

There is also growing resentment among young people towards Ruto, who came to power in 2022 promising rapid economic progress.

Many have been disillusioned by continued stagnation, corruption and high taxes, even after last year’s protests forced Ruto to cancel an unpopular finance bill. His government has been at pains to avoid direct tax rises this year.

But the frequent disappearances of government critics – rights groups have counted more than 80 since last year’s protests, with dozens still missing – have led many to accuse Ruto of returning Kenya to the dark days of its dictatorship in the 1980s and 90s.

Ruto previously promised an end to abductions but was unapologetic in a speech on Tuesday, pledging to “stand by” the police.
